Jama Masjid, Bhilai is one of the largest mosques in Chhattisgarh, India, with a capacity to accommodate more than 3000 worshippers at a time. It is the first mosque in the world to be built in the shape of the word "Ya Allah" in Arabic script. It took three years for the construction of the mosque which was completed in 1967.

HistoryEdit

Before the construction of the mosque the Muslims of Bhilai used to pray in their respective localities and gathered only on Eid al-Fitr and Eid al-Adha to offer common prayer near Nehru house of Culture in sector-1, Bhilai. The Muslim executives of Bhilai steel plant formed a committee and applied for its registration. It was registered as Bhilai Nagar Masjid Trust under Madhya Pradesh public Trust act 1951. The Bhilai steel plant allotted a plot measuring 12000 square feet in sector-6 to this committee for the Mosque. The construction began in 1964 and was completed in 1967. The first Friday prayer was held in the new mosque on 31 March 1967.

Architecture and designEdit

The special design of the mosque has created a history in the world of Islamic architecture through its monumental elevation which forms an Arabic word Yā Allāh (یا الله). The 80 feet high minar shapes ‘Ya’ while the concrete walls of the first floor with a slab above in the shape of tashdeed projects ‘Allah’. The marble dome at the top further enhances the beauty of this unique mosque in the world.

It was designed by the renowned architect Khairuddin Ahmad Siddiqui, Siddiqui and associates, Hyderabad, Telangana.

The mosque is 59 feet high, including the 16 feet high dome, 120 feet long and 100 feet wide. The Eid-gah adjacent to the mosque is 250 feet long and 230 feet wide. Marble tiles have been fixed inside and outside of the mosque’s minar. The mosque is maintained by the founding committee Bhilai Nagar Masjid Trust.

ImamsEdit

Alhaj Hafiz Sayed Ajmaluddin Haider served as the first Imam of this Mosque from 1968 to 2013. Born in Patna in 1942, his family moved permanently to Durg in 1952. His father, Maulana Afzaluddin Haidar became Imam of Jama Masjid Durg since 1952 whose mazaaris in Supela Kabristan, Bhilai. Alhaj Hafiz Sayed Ajmaluddin Haider is affiliated to Qadiriyyah Chishtiya Ashrafiya order of Sufism and is educated from Darul Uloom Islamia Nagpur.

Hafiz Iqbal Haider Anjum is the current Imam of the mosque who started serving from 1 January 2014. He is educated from Jame Ashraf, Kichaucha Shareef, Faizabad in Uttar Pradesh.

Welfare and developmentEdit

A Muslim community hall is built near mosque by the Bhilai Nagar masjid trust with the help of Muslims in Bhilai. The hall is 90 feet long, 42 feet wide and 22 feet high. A ladies’ hall has been partitioned out of it with approximately half of the total dimensions of the hall. The second floor is under construction and is estimated to be completed by the end of July 2015.

Representatives from non-Muslim communities - Sikh, Christian and Arya Samaj- visit every year to the mosque for wishing Muslims on the occasions of Eid conveying the spirit of inter-religious brotherhood and peace in Bhilai....😍 It is a matter of proud for our sector area that in our sector area of Chhattisgarh, Every kind of religion is discussed here.......🙏🏻✨

most_relevant.description:
Nestled in Deobaloda, near Bhilai–Charoda, the 13th-century Shiva temple—affectionately known as the “6-Maashi” or six-month temple—stands as a silent testament to Kalchuri-era craftsmanship. Built of red sandstone in the Nagara style, this east-facing temple comprises a garbhagriha (sanctum) and a pillared navaranga mandapa; notably, its shikhara (spire) remains unfinished—adding to its enigmatic charm .
As you approach, a Nandi sits vigilantly outside the entrance, while the pillars and walls are intricately carved with figures of Bhairava, Vishnu, Shiva, Mahishasuramardini, dancers, musicians, Kirtimukha motifs, and depictions of divine panels—like Tripurantaka, Narasimha, Radha-Krishna, Ganesh, and scenes of hunting and bull-fighting . Inside, a 1.5-ft Shiva lingam resides in the lower sanctum, flanked by idols of Parvati, Ganesh, Hanuman, Jagannath, and guardian dwarpalas at the ornately carved entrance .
Adding to the mystique is the temple’s kund (tank), believed to connect via a secret tunnel to Arang—accompanied by a local legend involving an engrossed sculptor whose dramatic story remains vivid in folklore .
Protected by the Archaeological Survey of India, the temple comes alive during Mahashivratri, attracting devotees from nearby villages with rituals and a small fair—offering an immersive spiritual and cultural experience .

The Dev Baloda Temple, standing for 600 years, holds a remarkable historical significance. However, the lack of visitor respect and improper maintenance is disheartening. The temple's serene atmosphere is marred by people touching sacred sculptures and littering the small park outside. Enhanced security measures and restrictions on idol interaction would preserve the temple's sanctity and cultural heritage. The sight of the Nandi idol wrapped in plastic and surrounded by ropes, yet still being touched by visitors, is a concerning reflection of the need for better preservation efforts.
14th century temple with a pond inside.

Also, spend some pleasant time near the pond beside which is said to have an underground tunnel opening in Arang. A must visit place for history, heritage, culture, archaeology, and architecture lovers.

This east facing edifice built of sand stone is surviving with a garbhagriha and a pillared Navaranga mandapa. The sikhara is missing which was probably in Nagara style. The garbhagriha houses a Shiv linga and is approached through a highly ornate entrance guarded by Saiva dwarapalas accompanied by attendants. Ganesha is depicted on the lalatabimba. The mandapa pillars are adorned with images of Bhairava, Vishnu, Mahishasurmardini, Tripurantaka Shiv, Venu Gopala, musicians, dancers, keertimukha designs etc.

The exterior of adhisthana portion of the temple bears decorative bands of Gaja, Asva and Nara. The Bhitti portion has two decorative segments, adorned with images of Tripuarantaka Shiv, Gajantakashiv, Narasimha, Nruvaraha, Parvati, Radha-Krishna, Ganesa, Mahishasurmardini, Laxmi,   Trivikrama,Venu Gopala, Kesi vadh etc. The temple constructed by the Kalachuris can be dated to 14th century AD. most_relevant.description: Maitri Bagh Zoo, Bhilai, a joint effort by India and Soviet Union and oldest zoo, is a delightful family outing. We enjoyed the pelicans, a large variety of birds, playful monkeys, storks and several deer species — the Bengal and white tigers were particularly majestic. The gardens are very well maintained with abundant trees, photographic sculptures and ample parking. The boating on the lake is relaxing and adds to the experience. Overall the park is clean, shady and child-friendly; great for weekend family visits.

Maitri Bagh, located in Bhilai, Chhattisgarh, is a well-known zoo and park that symbolizes the friendship between India and the Soviet Union. Its name translates to "Friendship Garden". Maintained by the Steel Authority of India Limited, it is one of the largest and oldest zoos in the region.

Maitri Bagh Zoo
Various types of birds, animals and aquatic animals are found here including white Tiger, Lion, Barahsingha are major attractions here. The park is full of greenary and peace. You can also the enjoy the boat ride.
Best time to visit is August to Feb - March

While my experience was great, I have a few suggestions that could enhance future visits:
Zoo Enclosure Maintenance: I noticed that some of the animal enclosures, particularly in the older sections of the zoo, could benefit from more consistent and detailed maintenance to improve hygiene and the overall presentation of the habitats.
Clarity of Service Timings: While the park and zoo timings are known, the operational times for attractions like the Boating and Toy Train were not immediately clear upon entry. Clearer signboards indicating the current operating hours for all activities would be very helpful.
Restroom Facilities: The cleanliness and upkeep of the public restroom facilities could be improved, particularly during peak hours, to match the standard of cleanliness maintained in the main garden areas.
Thank you once again for maintaining such a beautiful and valuable recreational space for the residents and visitors of Bhilai. I look forward to visiting again soon.

This square (chowk) is not properly designed. It's a danger zone in Bhilai. Roads are not straight towards the square.
Be careful while crossing it ☠️😁
Panthi Chowk in Bhilai is a great spot with tasty food, quick service, and a lively vibe. Perfect place for friends and family to enjoy a good meal!
There's nothing to attract tourists there. It could be a one-time watch but that too while you're crossing through it.

Panthi Chowk is a nightmare when it comes to traffic. The congestion here is not just frustrating but downright dangerous, with an average of one death every month. The roads are chaotic, with no proper traffic management, making it a constant risk for pedestrians and drivers alike. To make things worse, the food stalls lined up along the road add to the mess, creating bottlenecks and making the situation even more unbearable. It’s high time authorities take action to regulate traffic and relocate these stalls to a safer spot. Until then, Panthi Chowk remains a hazardous spot best avoided.
